p(x)
p(A)=\sin(A)
 A= \begin{bmatrix} \frac{\pi}{2} & 1 & 2 \\ 0 & \pi & 3 \\ 0 & 0 & -\pi \end{bmatrix} 
 \text{find}  \sin(A) 
 \text{I have found the spectral decomposition of A to be} 
 \frac{\pi}{2}E_1 + \pi E_2 - \pi E_3 
 E_{1}= \begin{bmatrix} 1 & -2\pi & \frac{4\pi -12}{3 \pi^{2}}\\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix} 
 E_{2}= \begin{bmatrix} 0 & \frac{2}{\pi} & \frac{3}{\pi^{2}}\\ 0 & 1 & \frac{3}{2\pi}\\ 0 & 0 & 0\\ \end{bmatrix} 
 E_{3}= \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 0 & \frac{3-4\pi}{3\pi^{2}}\\ 0 & 0 & \frac{-3}{2\pi}\\ 0 & 0 & 1\\ \end{bmatrix} 
 \sin(A)=\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)E_{1} + \sin(\pi)E_{2} - \sin(\pi)E_{3} \therefore \sin(A)=E_1 
A':=\begin{bmatrix} \pi/2 &0&0 \\ 0&\pi&0 \\ 0&0&-\pi \end{bmatrix}
A
v_1,v_2,v_3
B:=\left[ v_1|v_2|v_3 \right]
A
A'
(BAB^{-1})^n = BA^nB^{-1}
\sin
A=BA'B^{-1}
p(A)=B\cdot p(A')\cdot B^{-1}\ \text{ and }\ \sin(A) = B\cdot \sin(A')\cdot B^{-1} 
p(A)=\sin(A) \iff p(A')=\sin(A')
